Too risky a move to drop 15 tons like that. The allosaur wouldn't need to turn, just pull back a bit.

@SurvivalStee @AllosaurusJP I disagree that there's no way it could avoid it. Allosaurs were likely very agile and if the sauropod is on the floor and has hurt itself trying to fall on the allo, it's screwed. Unlikely an animal would put itself at risk like that.
@SurvivalStee @AllosaurusJP An incredibly risky move that would make it incredibly vulnerable if the allosaur dodged it. If it fell over too quickly it could hurt itself too.
@SurvivalStee @AllosaurusJP Like I said, this is no way me saying the allo would be in with a good chance, just that a lone sauropod is not a sure win. The allosaur has a chance.

@SurvivalStee @AllosaurusJP Lions hunting style is based around grappling, favouring pack hunting, whereas allosaur teeth were serrated and it would have been more suited to slicing out chunks and backing off, same as sharks.

@SurvivalStee @AllosaurusJP Gravity and weight also reduce agility. A saurpod would have to swing around, making it effective from the front and back but vulnerable from the sides. @draken_rox @DanPalaeon1 I'm not shutting down anything. I share a lot of the sentiments shared here. I'm just saying what they're doing isn't out of ignorance of science, it's a deliberate deviation to appeal to a pop culture idea of what dinosaurs should be.
@RauppLopes @DanPalaeon1 Except that's not what their intention is. That's my point. They want to create pop culture movie monsters based on dinosaurs, not scientifically accurate representations.

@FabioAleRomero @DanPalaeon1 I want to emphasise that I agree that the JW designs are often ugly and diverge from science in unnecessary ways, I'm just saying that we need to understand that isn't a concern for their vision. They know what they're doing. It's a deliberate choice.

@FabioAleRomero @DanPalaeon1 Sure, you can pick accurate retro dinosaur designs just as easily as you can find inaccurate ones. There were lots of great retro palaeoartists, and lots of bad ones that filtered into pop culture. Gurney was one of the better ones.
@DanPalaeon1 Completely disagree. Looks like countless retro dinosaur figures I had or saw growing up (non-Jurassic Park ones). It could totally be a generic Allosaurid though.

@draken_rox @DanPalaeon1 Because dinosaurs as real animals and dinosaurs as a part of pop culture are two entirely different things, and the JW movies are more concerned with the latter. There's an aesthetic they're going for that is in conflict with the science.

@jasonm221b @DanPalaeon1 Again, completely different team with a different vision. My comment was merely to suggest we need to realise that they know what they're doing, it's intentional that they don't follow the science. You can't expect accuracy from these movies anymore.

@DanPalaeon1 It's a different design team and studio working on these films now though, with a completely different vision. They're embracing a more retrosaur design aesthetic. I think the Giga is fine tbh, not one of the worst offenders.

@DanPalaeon1 People need to understand that their priority is always creating memorable movie monsters. Scientific accuracy is merely a guide they can apply as desired. I have a love/hate relationship with the designs post-JW but I accept them for what they are - movie monsters, not animals.
